Here's an example of HTML code using Google Charts API to display a column chart comparing the population growth rate of America, Germany, China, and India:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <script type="text/javascript" src="https://www.gstatic.com/charts/loader.js"></script>
    <script type="text/javascript">
      google.charts.load('current', {'packages':['corechart']});
      google.charts.setOnLoadCallback(drawChart);

      function drawChart() {

        var data = google.visualization.arrayToDataTable([
          ['Country', 'Population Growth Rate'],
          ['America',  1.05],
          ['Germany',  0.25],
          ['China',  0.7],
          ['India',  1.2]
        ]);

        var options = {
          title: 'Population Growth Rate in Different Countries',
          chartArea: {width: '50%'},
          hAxis: {
            title: 'Population Growth Rate',
            minValue: 0
          },
          vAxis: {
            title: 'Country',
            textStyle: {
              fontSize: 12
            }
          }
        };

        var chart = new google.visualization.BarChart(document.getElementById('chart_div'));

        chart.draw(data, options);
      }
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <div id="chart_div"></div>
  </body>
</html>
```

Replace the values with the actual population growth rate numbers for each country.

Here is a C program that takes an array as input and calculates the sum of all of its elements:

```
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int array[] = {2, 4, 3, 7, 5};
    int i, sum = 0;
    int n = sizeof(array)/sizeof(array[0]);

    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        sum += array[i];
    }

    printf("Sum of all array elements = %d\n", sum);
    return 0;
}
```
In the above program, we first declare an array with 5 elements `{2,4,3,7,5}`. We also declare two integer variables `i` and `sum`. The variable `i` is used as a counter in the `for` loop and `sum` is used to store the final result of the sum of all array elements. To calculate the number of elements in the array, we divide the size of the entire array by the size of one element using the `sizeof()` function. The `for loop` is used to iterate over each element of the array and add its value to the `sum` variable. Finally, we print the value of `sum` which gives us the sum of all elements in the array.
